                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 2.  <span>Allometric scaling of reticulocyte count.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p1"></a><p>We plot the logarithm of reticulocyte count of a given mammal as a function of the logarithm of its mass (in gram).</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p2" name="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p2"></a><p>Plotted data correspond to a total of 40 mammal species with masses ranging over 6 orders of magnitude, from voles to whales.</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p3" name="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p3"></a><p>The data corresponds to the mean value of the reticulocyte count for each species.</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p4" name="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p4"></a><p>A straight linear fit leads to a coefficient of 0.745, remarkably close to the ¾ exponent (R<sup>2</sup> = 0.94, p&lt;0.0001, CI 0.70–0.76), with an intercept of 7.641.</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p5" name="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p5"></a><p>Hence for the smallest mammal (a shrew with ~3 gram), we predict a reticulocyte count of ~1×10<sup>8</sup>.</p>
